Review: I keep rewatching movies I don't like that much something wrong with my brain.

Now that it is my third time watching this film, I can confidently say that The Wailing is total nonsense. No one on Earth except maybe the writer-director Na Hong-Jin can give an explanation of what this film is supposed to be about. The Wailing is incoherent in plot and unintelligible in meaning, and that is assuming that there even is a meaning. I guess the director is telling us to not trust minorities or something.Don't mind me though.…
I did not care at all.

In the age of social media and A.I. generated content, Videodrome's central message of mass media ushering in an age of competing hallucinations is more prescient than it ever was. Our democracies were already fucked with all the news channels and newspapers actively trying to manipulate citizens' needs and wants according to elite desires. I am not peddling conspiracy theories, there are valid statistical studies on how Murdoch media has made people more Republican and anti-EU. And now, we have…

How often do you see a movie about motorcyclist knights jousting which is actually about an artists' struggle to maintain his artistic integrity when faced with capitalism? Never, if you haven't seen Knightriders yet, that is. This film is absolutely crazy and I respect it immensely, even though it's definitely way too long.
Funny how the egotistical and deluded professor who dedicated his life to living until 120 died the earliest out of the group.
Hits different when you see it in theaters on a rainy night, and afterwards have to go to your shithole house located on Vienna's center of prostitution.

Colossus, this film's titular A.I., has processed all of humankind's historical and philosophical works. And what has this immense amount of data taught him? What profound conclusion has the most intelligent 'being' in all of history reached? "Freedom is an illusion." Really? And this is portrayed as the ultimate rational thought.I have seen a lot of fiction that tackles A.I., and it is tiring how most of them portray hyper-intelligent A.I. as a 'benevolent dictator.' These A.I. never do…

Junk Head is the product of one middle-aged Japanese man's diseased mind. The film's director/cinematographer/editor/writer/composer/actor Takahide Hori does a bang-up job creating an atmospheric, post-apocalyptic comedy. Truly an auteur's film.
A demented rooster terrorizing an Indian family intercut with the family's father assuring the viewers that he will eventually decapitate and eat the rooster no matter the protests.
